Even though there is a growing body of scholars who argue that participation in the 1033 Program makes an excellent test case for theories of police militarization (Ajilore, 2015; Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Dansky, 2014; Delehanty et al., 2017; Harris et al., 2017; McQuoid and Vitt, 2017; Radil, Dezzani, and McAden, 2017), it is not an exhaustive indicator of police militarization.1 We focus on the 1033 Program, however, because accessing materiel such as weaponry, vehicles, and uniforms is an early and often necessary step for many LEAs toward further militarization in the dimensions of language and terminology, organizing using military principles, and practicing military-style tactics (Ajilore, 2015; Insler, McMurray, and McQuoid, 2016; Kraska, 1996; Phillips, 2016). Moreover, the fact that the 1033 Program provides free materiel allows resource-poor LEAs the capacity to create PPUs and emulate policing efforts that may otherwise only occur in larger, better resourced departments (Dansky, 2014; Radil, Dezzani, and McAden, 2017).
The process for obtaining 1033 Program materiel is not difﬁcult for LEAs and does not distinguish between combat and noncombat gear (Bruce et al., 2017; Harris et al., 2017). The ﬁrst step is for the LEA to register with the 1033 Program by submitting a two-page form. Once an LEA is registered and decides to request materiel, the head administrator requests, via another form, speciﬁc materiel (e.g., ﬁrearms, armored vehicles, aircraft, or any other gear; Bruce et al., 2017; Defense Logistics Agency, 2016a; Harris et al., 2017). Other than the subordinate relationship that leaders of law enforcement have with local political leaders (e.g., mayors and local councils; Jacobs and O’Brien, 1998), there is little community oversight into the types of property LEAs acquire each year (Bruce et al., 2017).
Once a request is approved, the 1033 Program provides the requested equipment to LEAs (Defense Logistics Agency, 2016a; Grasso, 2014). The only ﬁnancial cost to LEAs in this process is shipping charges. The availability of materiel, and its disposition to LEAs nationwide, is mainly determined by U.S. military engagements abroad and DoD decisions regarding the equipment that active military use when they are deployed (e.g., military drawdowns in Iraq and Afghanistan increased the availability of MRAPs for LEAs). Currently, the DoD does not evaluate the social control needs of an LEA’s request for 1033 Program materiel, although the 1033 Program does prioritize requests that cite drug law enforcement or counterterrorism efforts and requires that departments plan to use the materiel for valid law enforcement efforts within the year.

THEORIES OF SOCIAL CONTROL AND THE POLICE
Although few dispute the fact that the police are increasingly adopting military practices and equipment, and that the 1033 Program may be inﬂuencing that trend, we know little about the determinants of 1033 Program acquisitions by LEAs. As such, to inform our assessment of militarization in the material dimension in the 1033 Program, we turn to

