RATIONAL PUBLIC CHOICE
By drawing on econometric arguments for crime and crime control (Becker, 1968), rational public choice theories of social control presume that police departments will intensify social control efforts when facing greater demands to stop crime (Nagin, 1998; Stucky, 2005). As such, rational public choice theories posit that increases in policing efﬁcacy (be it by expanding police forces, increasing funding, or improving overall competence) may increase the police’s deterrent effect against crime and disorder (Cohen and Felson, 1979; Nagin, 1998).2
In this sense, police militarization may be seen as a rational public choice police response to social control demands that stem from high crime rates, participation in drug interdictions, threats to public safety, or even threats to the police themselves (Hall and Coyne, 2013). Indeed, Phillips (2016) argued that perceptions of lethal danger to police ofﬁcers, and an institutional ethos of police as crime ﬁghters, have become justiﬁcations for police to seek and carry military-style “patrol” riﬂes as a reasonable (yet unproven) response to criminal, terrorist, and mass shooter threats that have recently increased demands on LEAs for public security. Similarly, Kraska and Kappeler (1997) found that a primary justiﬁcation for the existence of many paramilitary police units (PPUs, or SWAT units) is a belief that such gear and tactics improved LEA efforts at hot-spots policing, a policing strategy itself predicated on rational public choice theories of deterrence (Braga, Papachristos, and Hureau, 2014; Cohen and Felson, 1979; Roncek and Maier, 1991). Furthermore, Bell (1982: 47) argued that many police uniforms use military stylings to convey authority and power as general criminal deterrents, going so far as to say that police have “confused the desire to be military with the need to appear uniform and identiﬁable.” Bell’s (1982) insights are still relevant today as more and more LEAs may not simply add militaristic ﬂair to their uniforms but fully adopt military fatigues and tactical vests used by the military to deter criminals (DeMichele and Kraska, 2001).
Following the rational public choice argument of policing, the acquisition of military equipment may serve as a means to improve LEAs’ capacity to respond to crime or public safety crises. Indeed, recent research ﬁndings reveal that 1033 Program materiel acquisitions are associated with reductions in the rates of violent crime and property crime (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017) and with increases in drug arrest rates (Harris et al., 2017), although these ﬁndings are unclear on whether crime or arrest rates inﬂuence demand for 1033 Program materiel. If police militarization is indeed a response to increased demands on LEAs to produce social control, we anticipate that 1033 Program participation will be greater in places where police departments are called to respond to high violent crime rates, improve the arrest capabilities in of drug enforcement efforts, and effectively prepare for potential threats to public safety.

