MINORITY THREAT
Minority threat perspectives of social control are based on conﬂict theories predicated on racial/ethnic cleavages. Blalock (1967) theorized that increases in minority group presence create perceptions of racial competition with dominant majority groups. As a reaction to perceptions of competition for political and economic resources, the majority group may respond to minority group threats with harsher law enforcement practices (Liska, 1992). Later research ﬁndings on minority threat theories revealed that prejudiced attitudes in majority groups can indeed be associated with the presence of racial minorities (Giles and Buckner, 1993; Quillian, 1995, 1996; Taylor, 1998). In this way, crime control becomes a means for racial majorities to protect their status by pacifying or eliminating threatening minority groups (Behrens, Uggen, and Manza, 2003; Olzak, 1992; Spitzer, 1975).
When the percentage of Blacks, Hispanics, and non-White minorities in cities as an indicator of minority threat have been used, scholars in multiple studies have found a link between increased minority presence and larger police forces and police spending (Jackson, 1989; Jackson and Carroll, 1981; Kent and Jacobs, 2005; Liska, Lawrence, and Benson, 1981; Sharp, 2006; Stucky, 2005). In other studies, scholars have found that such minority threat explanations can also account for disparate minority incarceration rates (Bridges and Crutchﬁeld, 1988; Garofalo, 1980), sentencing outcomes (Crawford, Chiricos, and Kleck, 1998; Johnson, 2005; Sampson and Laub, 1993; Ulmer and Johnson, 2004), and the use of extralegal violence against minorities (Chamlin, 1989; Holmes, 2000; Jacobs, Carmichael, and Kent, 2005; Jacobs and Wood, 1999; Sorensen, Marquart, and Brock, 1993). In short, the link between minority threat, the allocation of criminal justice resources, and the use of violent social control has emerged as a consistent ﬁnding in criminological research.
Although previous research ﬁndings have provided support to the notion that racial Whites are the dominant majority in the United States, there is some question about which racial minority group is the most threatening to this majority group and whether similar relationships between minority prevalence and social control practices exist across different minorities. Even though most studies of minority threat have been focused on Black populations (Jackson, 1989; Keen and Jacobs, 2009; King, 2008), others have produced results that reveal that Hispanic populations also produce threat responses from Whites (Kane, 2003; Kent and Jacobs, 2005; Stewart et al., 2015). It is theoretically plausible that any minority group can constitute a threat to a majority once it is large enough (Blalock, 1967); therefore, to assess minority threat explanations accurately, we must capture multiple measures of racial and ethnic minorities.
Scholars testing minority threat explanations often ﬁnd the relationship between minority group threat and the allocation of criminal justice resources to be nonlinear. Blalock (1967) originally postulated that although perceptions of racial competition increase linearly with minority group presence, discriminatory responses against minority groups (such as disproportionate criminal justice resource allocation) would be nonlinear (Blalock, 1967: 140–7). According to Blalock (1967: 147–50), discriminatory actions cumulative in their effect to hinder minority competition would have a functional form that indicates a curvilinear relationship as the cumulative effect of discrimination to prevent threats reduced the need for harsher responses as minority presence grew. Discriminatory efforts, however, not cumulative in their effect to prevent minority competition would

