motivate discriminatory responses that exponentially increased with minority group presence (Blalock, 1967: 1950–4).3
Although arguments for nonlinear responses have informed a broader conversation about the functional forms in minority threat and social control (Liska, 1992), researchers on minority threat and policing have regularly found nonlinear minority threat responses that vary in their functional form. Jacobs (1979) found that city-level police forces increase linearly with Black populations. Jackson and Carrol (1981), in their work on city-level police force spending, discovered that police spending increased until Black populations reached 50 percent and then declined for higher percentages. Kent and Jacobs (2005) and Kane (2003) likewise found a curvilinear relationship for police spending, increasing exponentially once Hispanic populations reached ß20 percent of the population in a locality. Furthermore, Stucky (2005) revealed a curvilinear association between police force size and both Black and Hispanic populations that was conditional upon the political context of city governments. Stults and Baumer (2007) similarly found county police force sizes increased at a decreasing rate until county populations reached 20 percent Black; then police force size began to decline. Given the wide range of ﬁndings between different minority groups and the variety of functional forms in criminal justice responses, in our assessment of 1033 Program participation, we consider functional forms of minority threat that might not be consistent across different racial and ethnic minority groups. It is also crucial, however, to understand how 1033 Program participation and the acquisition of militarized equipment may constitute a police response to minority threat, which leads us to explore the connection between race and police militarization.

1033 PROGRAM PARTICIPATION AS MINORITY THREAT RESPONSE
Although ecological associations have remained unexamined, previous research ﬁndings suggest that race is likely a factor in police militarization. In their seminal work on the expansion of police militarization, Kraska and Kappeler quoted an interview with a police commander who stated that the use of military equipment and tactics were meant to target “suspicious vehicles and people. We stop anything that moves. We’ll sometimes even surround suspicious homes and bring out the MP5s. We usually don’t have any problems with crack-heads” (1997: 10). The mention of using submachine guns (MP5s) to eliminate “problems” speaks to the intended symbolic threat of military gear in police work mentioned earlier, whereas the mention of suspicious vehicles can also have racial connotations (Kowalski and Lundman, 2007). At the same time, the mention of “crack-heads” belies the differential enforcement of drug laws against crack-cocaine users, who tend to be poor and Black, compared with powder-cocaine users, who tend to be wealthier and White (Alexander, 2012). Even more explicit in linking racial bias to police militarization, Kraska and Kappeler (1997: 10) later quoted a PPU commander, who stated that “when the soldiers ride in you should see those blacks scatter.”

