Although policy proponents contend that 1033 Program participation is a race-neutral response to violent crime and terrorism, pervasive stereotypes of minorities as criminogenic and threatening to Whites suggest to us that 1033 Program participation speciﬁcally, and police militarization generally, may be inﬂuenced by minority group presence (Balko, 2013; Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Kraska, 2001). Meeks (2006) argued that police militarization constitutes an “obscure war against the urban underclass” motivated by shifting federal funds from social programs meant to aid minority communities into tough-on-crime programs, a trend occurring since the late 1960s (Hinton, 2016). These efforts to increase state social control in minority communities while diverting funds from social welfare programs to crime-control efforts are consistent with Wacquant’s (2009) critiques. Thus, police have been able to justify the acquisition and use of military equipment and PPUs to conduct a variety of practices, from routine patrols to no-knock drug raids in minority communities deﬁned as “problems” by police and politicians (Balko, 2013; Hinton, 2016; Kraska and Kappeler, 1997; Meeks, 2006; Phillips et al., 2016).
Perceptions of minorities as threatening to Whites, as well as law enforcement and policy maker responses to such threats, are well documented. Russell-Brown (1998) demonstrated that despite appeals of “color-blindness” from lawmakers and the police, White fears and stereotypes of criminal behavior remain dominated by racial biases that allow the proliferation of racial hoaxes like the “criminalblackman” stereotype. Indeed, popular perceptions of minority groups as criminogenic may inﬂuence policy leaders and law enforcement to view minority group presence as evidence of crime-control demand (Alexander, 2012; Du Bois, 1994 [1903]; Hinton, 2016; Weaver, 2007). Weaver (2007) also noted that the creation of the Law Enforcement Assistance Administration (LEAA) in 1968, the ﬁrst federal initiative to provide federal funds and military equipment to local police, was in part a response to White perceptions of Black civil rights mobilization as criminal. Jackson and Carroll (1981), in their earlier work linking LEAA funding for police departments with a curvilinear minority threat response to Black population size and civil rights mobilization, further supported the idea that police militarization is minority threat response. Similarly, Hinton (2016) also noted that some of the earliest arguments for issuing military equipment to police—and some of the earliest efforts to issue the equipment—were motivated by White fears of urban Black rioters after the Watts and Detroit riots. In short, if we follow the argument that an increase in minority groups also increases the perception of threats to social order (Blalock, 1967), which in turn incites punitive responses from the majority (Jacobs and Helms, 1999; Quillian, 1995, 1996; Taylor, 1998), and that the use of military equipment allows police to respond with greater force (Kraska, 2007), then the link between police militarization and minority presence is plausible.
It is unknown whether minority presence may account for recent 1033 Program participation independent of the previously argued rational public choice explanations. Although a viable minority threat explanation of police militarization can be made based on previous research aimed at examining threats to the political status quo from the civil rights movement (Hinton, 2016; Jackson and Carroll, 1981; Weaver, 2007), Blalock (1967), in his original argument for nonlinear minority threat responses, suggests that perceived threats to political power should elicit discriminatory responses that increase at an increasing rate until a minority group’s size reaches a point at which its political and economic power becomes sufﬁcient to resist such discrimination efforts (Stucky, 2005; Stults and Baumer, 2007). The minority threat response to Black populations, however, may not

