RESEARCH QUESTIONS
The earlier discussion of rational choice and minority threat explanations for police militarization motivates our research questions regarding local law enforcement’s participation in the 1033 Program. First, do rational public choice theories of police strength explain participation in the 1033 Program? If so, we should anticipate that high crime rates, violent threats to police, and terrorist threats create demand for increased police security, predicating 1033 Program participation. Second, is minority threat a determinant of participation in the 1033 Program? Third, and relatedly, given that minority threats produce nonlinear responses from majority groups, if minority threat is a determinant of police militarization, what is the functional form of this relationship? In the following analyses, we assess these three research questions by examining both rational public choice and minority threat explanations that account for the likelihood of an LEA to participate in the 1033 Program and the value of materiel obtained by the participant LEAs. Finally, given that the 1033 Program can supplement police work with noncombat gear (Bruce et al., 2017), as well as combat materiel (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Harris et al., 2017), it is crucial for an assessment of 1033 Program participation as a test of police militarization to account for the qualitative nature of equipment obtained. Thus, we pose a fourth question: Do rational public choice and/or minority threat accounts of police miltiarization explain the aquistion of military equipment as opposed to nonmilitary equipment?

DATA AND METHOD
1033 PROGRAM DATA
Our primary source of data is the DoD’s Defense Logistics Agency Law Enforcement Support Ofﬁce (LESO) 1033 Program. The LESO was created in 1995 to work exclusively with local law enforcement and to improve the effectiveness of the program, which had been rarely used until then. The LESO records the value of the property supplied to LEAs as the value it had when obtained by the military. It also provides users with federal supply category and class names used by the military, itemized details using NATO Stock Numbers (NSN), and the date, location, and name of LEAs receiving military equipment. Thanks to the Freedom of Information Act, these 1033 Program data are publicly available (Defense Logistics Agency, 2016b). As discussed earlier, the 1033 Program provides a wide variety of materiel, combat and noncombat, with LEAs only having to cover the costs of shipping. We used LESO descriptions and federal supply categories and classes

