in these data to code materiel received by LEAs as either militarized or nonmilitarized. We present a list of militarized and nonmilitarized materiel in appendices A and B.
Our conceptualization of militarized equipment is informed by Kraska’s (2007: 503) deﬁnition of militarism, such that we identiﬁed militarized equipment sent to LEAs as equipment that stresses “the use of force and threat of violence” and may help LEAs to prepare for and implement violence as a solution to problems, as well as to dominate in any situation in which violence might arise. Examples of militarized property include munitions (e.g., ﬁrearms, explosives, and missile launchers); militarized transportation (e.g., armored trucks, MRAPs, airplanes, and helicopters); military communication or surveillance equipment (e.g., night-vision goggles and wide-range radio antennae); uniforms (e.g., body armor and specialized combat clothing); and miscellaneous items, including weapons-training guides, crowd-control equipment, and aftermarket armor for vehicles (a.k.a. up-armor kits).
We conceptualize nonmilitarized equipment as property received by agencies that does not facilitate the use or threat of violence or provide police ofﬁcers with a signiﬁcant tactical advantage in wielding violence. Examples of nonmilitarized property include ofﬁce supplies and computers (e.g., hardware, software, furniture, and supplies); standard telecommunications equipment (e.g., ﬁber optics, radar, and video recording); clothing (e.g., socks and underwear); agricultural and industrial tools (e.g., pest control, hand tools, laboratory supplies, and generators); safety and rescue equipment (e.g., ﬁre-ﬁghting and hazardous spill and containment); and health and medical supplies (e.g., ﬁeld medical kits, portable reagents, and IV ﬂuids). Additionally, we consider items that agencies may use in conjunction with militarized materiel but that have universal purposes (e.g., aircraft maintenance equipment and engine accessories) to be nonmilitarized. Finally, we consider items that are primarily used in emergency or disaster response (e.g., water puriﬁcation systems and ordinance disposal kits) to be nonmilitarized.
Although our conceptualization of militarized and nonmilitarized property is rooted in prior theory and based on the intended or original use of the materiel, we recognize that tactical and combat equipment can be implemented for nonmilitarized purposes (e.g., search and rescue). For example, police departments in Harris County, Texas, credit the MRAPs they received through the 1033 Program for assisting in search and rescue operations after Hurricane Harvey (Blakinger, 2017), and Miami Beach police argue they need MRAPs to drive through ﬂoods and help with evacuation and protection during potential mass shooting situations (Iannelli, 2014). Although these uses reﬂect larger trends in the changing responsibilities of police in general (Beck and Goldstein, 2017; Simon, 2007), the war on drugs and the ability to maintain a superior force in the threat of potential violence remain the primary initial reasons for acquiring property from the 1033 Program (Apuzzo, 2014; DLA, 2016b; Grasso, 2014; Iannelli, 2017). Finally, regardless of how departments use MRAPs and other militarized property, the acquisition of such materiel is associated with harsh and overbearing policing in both police practice (Delehanty et al., 2017) and public opinion (Carriere and Encinosa, 2017).
Although participation in the 1033 Program provides limited evidence of police militarization, our approach and data offer an in-depth assessment of the materiel LEAs are receiving via the 1033 Program, which may facilitate further militarization of LEAs, and the ecological determinants of such acquisitions. Because the 1033 Program provides materiel at low cost and with few restrictions, an examination of 1033 Program participation provides insight into police decision-making that is less inﬂuenced by

