political and institutional factors than others forms of police militarization (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Harris et al., 2017). As such, our primary motivation in this study is to offer an unprecedented assessment of the ecological factors explaining the transfer of $5 billion in lethal and nonlethal materiel to local law enforcement at little cost, with little oversight, and amidst a growing amount of public criticism and concern.
After identifying the 1033 Program property as militarized or nonmilitarized and aggregating annual values for number and acquisition value for each agency, we merge the 1033 Program data to crime and arrest data from the Uniform Crime Reports (UCR) and LEOKA data using the state and agency name. We combine our agency-level data with data from the U.S. Census, American Community Survey, Congressional Quarterly Voting and Elections Collection, and the National Consortium for the Study of Terrorism and Responses to Terrorism (START) Global Terrorism Database, using the UCR Crosswalk and addresses provided to the UCR.
SAMPLE
Because the law enforcement responsibilities of county and state agencies differ greatly from state to state and serve overlapping geographies and populations as cities and towns, we exclude county and state agencies, as well as specialized forces (e.g., university campuses and school districts), and focus on local (cities and towns) law enforcement agencies, as deﬁned in LEOKA. We then link each local law enforcement agency to the Census place that best reﬂects its jurisdiction. This includes all incorporated places (e.g., cities, towns outside of the Northeast and Midwest, villages, and boroughs); Census-designated places (e.g., towns/townships in the Northeast and Midwest, unincorporated places in New England City and Town Areas, Consolidated Cities, and unincorporated statistical places with a police force).4 In most places, only one law enforcement agency operates and police chiefs and administrators are often required to work with, and answer to, local elected ofﬁcials (e.g., mayors and city councilmembers) on law enforcement matters. In places where more than one local agency operates, typically one local department and multiple task forces or special units focus on different aspects of law enforcement (e.g., local liquor control).
Although data on military transfers are available dating back to the inception of the program in 1989, we reduce our analytic sample to the years between 1995 and 2016.5 We wish to focus on the period since the creation of the LESO, which is responsible for managing the program and which works exclusively with law enforcement (DLA, 2016b), to separate the limited scope of the program during its earliest years from more recent trends in police militarization as a general approach to policing (Balko, 2013). Although the amount of property increased substantially during the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq, we include prewar years (1995–2002) to capture the period in which Kraska and colleagues ﬁrst identiﬁed trends in police militarization in the criminological literature (Balko, 2013; Kraska, 1996; Kraska and Cubellis, 1997; Kraska and Kappeler, 1997) and to account for early adopters of police militarization through the 1033 Program.

