We exclude several LEAs for varying reasons. Because of their unique geographic and racial/ethnic contexts, we exclude Alaskan and Hawaiian agencies from all analyses. Because of the unique relationship between the federal government and D.C. law enforcement, we exclude the District of Columbia PD and DC Metro Police. After excluding agencies serving extremely small places (maximum yearly population between 1994 and 2015 of less than 500) and those agencies that never reported to the UCR between 1994 and 2015, our ﬁnal sample size consists of 238,013 department-years’ worth of data from 11,764 local police departments.
DEPENDENT VARIABLES
Our dependent variables capture the annual value (as recorded by the LESO) of militarized and nonmilitarized equipment per 10,000 persons (place population) obtained by individual local law enforcement agencies from the 1033 Program between 1995 and 2016. This measure allows us to account for the decision to participate in the 1033 Program, the degree to which LEAs are adding to their inventories, and the variation in types of military equipment that are available from year to year.
INDEPENDENT VARIABLES
Rational Public Choice Explanations
The predominate conventional explanations for police militarization speciﬁcally, and for aggressive policing generally, have been high rates of crime, risks to ofﬁcer safety, and the changing role of domestic law enforcement in addressing both domestic and foreign terrorist threats. In particular, drug enforcement efforts, and violent crime associated with such efforts, remain the most frequently cited reasons given by law enforcement to explain aggressive policies (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; den Heyer, 2014; Harris et al., 2017; Kappeler and Kraska, 2015). For example, police departments that report high rates of violent crime may need superior weapons, armored vehicles, and better surveillance and communications equipment to protect ofﬁcers and detain criminals (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Harris et al., 2017). We measure violent crime rates using the number of homicides, aggravated assaults, robberies, and forcible rapes per 10,000 place population.
Although the 1033 Program made materiel available for efforts outside of drug interdiction in 1997, more than half of the requests from departments are for drug enforcement (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; DLA, 2016b). Departments in counties with lower levels of drug arrests may view their enforcement efforts as ineffective, motivating them to participate in the 1033 Program for materiel that might improve their ability to detect and arrest criminals in the war on drugs. We include a measure of drug arrest rates using the county-level number of drug arrests (possession and sales) per 10,000 county population.6 We choose a county-level measure of drug arrests task forces, as opposed to local arrests, for several reasons. First, buoyed by the recognition that drug dealers do not recognize

