In addition to ﬁghting violent crime and the war on drugs, police departments are now also expected to engage in counter-terror efforts. Departments in places that experience terrorism may be more likely to participate in the 1033 Program than departments in other places. We measure recent terror attack with a dummy variable equal to 1 for departments in places that have experienced at least one terror attack in the past 3 years using data from the START Global Terrorism Database (National Consortium for the Study of Terrorism and Responses to Terrorism, 2015).7 Finally, the LESO provides access to vehicles and equipment that offer police more protection than common police cruisers and weapons. As a result, departments that have experienced police fatalities may be more likely to participate in the 1033 Program. We use LEOKA data to measure recent ofﬁcer fatalities using the total number of ofﬁcers killed on duty (felony and nonfelony) over the past 3 years per 100 ofﬁcers.8

Minority Threat Explanations
We measure minority threat using data from the 1990 and 2000 U.S. Census, and because the American Community Survey replaced the long-form version of the decennial census, we use the 2005–2009, 2006–2010, 2007–2011, 2008–2012, 2009–2013, 2010– 2014, 2011–2015, and 2012–2016 ﬁve-year ACS samples to construct our minority threat measures.
We test for different nonlinear relationships between racial and ethnic composition and the likelihood of participation in the 1033 Program as well as the value of materiel acquired by participating departments (Blalock, 1967; King and Wheelock, 2007; Stults and Baumer, 2007; Wang and Mears, 2010). We anticipate that racial and ethnic threat has a curvilinear relationship with participating in the 1033 Program and acquiring militarized property, but this relationship may be quadratic or logarithmic. As a result, we assess linear, quadratic, and natural logarithmic forms for percent Black (percent Black) and percent Hispanic (percent Hispanic) in our probit models predicting the receipt of any militarized property from the 1033 Program and our ordinary least-squares (OLS)

