Control Variables
We include several measures that could explain participation in the 1033 Program and the acquisition of high-value property at a discounted cost. Several scholars have contrasted racialized crime theories such as racial threat with conﬂict theories rooted in neo-Marxian perspectives of power and crime control (Rusche and Kircshheimer, 1939; Spitzer, 1975; Turk, 1969). Generally speaking, these arguments hold that large populations of the poor and unemployed present signiﬁcant threats to economic and political elites, who use their inﬂuence to address these threats with criminal justice practices like policing (Carmichael and Kent, 2014; Kent and Jacobs, 2005; Stucky, 2005; Stucky, Heimer, and Lang, 2007). We use two variables that capture different aspects of economic conﬂict that may affect the ability of local law enforcement to access military gear through the 1033 Program. We measure the poverty rate as the percentage of the relevant jurisdiction living under the poverty line. We measure the unemployment rate as the percentage of the relevant jurisdiction that is out of work.
Because larger police departments may need more materiel for their ofﬁcers, we include a measure of police ofﬁcers per 10,000 population. Research ﬁndings show that politicians and localities supportive of the Republican Party tend to support increases in police expenditures, corrections expenditures, and punitive criminal justice polices (Beckett, 1999; Jacobs and Carmichael, 2002; Jacobs and Helms, 1999). Since police militarization operates to make law enforcement more punitive and coercive, we anticipate that localities supportive of the Republican Party may be inclined to pursue police militarization. Using data from the Congressional Quarterly Voting and Elections Collection, we measure political attitudes using the percentage of the county voting for the most recent Republican presidential candidate and interpolated for nonelection years (percent Republican). We control for regional differences in policing and access to military equipment using dummy variables for Midwest (reference), Northeast, South, and West Census regions, and for population size using the natural log to account for skew and nonlinearity.
We include several controls that capture the practical restraints that LEAs face when participating in the 1033 Program. First, we include a measure of average distance to DLA disposition centers. Because departments are required to cover the costs to inspect and transport property from DLA disposition centers to their agencies, we assume that departments closer to these centers will be more likely to acquire militarized property. We also recognize that if departments are seeking out a speciﬁc item, they may be willing to pay to ship it long distances. Relatedly, if departments are shipping from a long distance, they may request and acquire property of a greater value to maximize their shipping costs. We use the natural log of our distance variable to account for skew and nonlinearity. We control for land area (in logged square kilometers) because the 1033 Program gives priority to departments serving larger jurisdictions in terms of land, particularly for vehicles. We include a measure of lagged total property value to control for recent 1033 Program

