MISSING DATA
There are two sources of missing data in our sample. First, because we use Census and ACS data for our demographic and social variables, we do not have measures for intercensal years (1997–1999, 2001–2008). We address this concern using linear interpolation to calculate year-by-year measures between the Census and ACS data points. This approach constructs new data points for observations between two or more known data points and is common strategy for handling the years between the Census and ACS in demographic (Crowder, Pais, and South, 2012; Ludwig et al., 2012) and criminological research (Eason, Zucker, and Wildeman, 2017; Parker, Mancik, and Stansﬁeld, 2017; Xie and McDowall, 2014).12 The second source of missing data is agency nonparticipation in UCR or LEOKA. After removing agencies that we could not locate any data on for the entire study period (1995–2015), slightly more than 6 percent of our agency-years contain missing data on either violent crime or drug arrests. We employ multiple imputation techniques to estimate these missing values using the “ICE” command in Stata 15.0 (Royston, 2005). ICE uses a chained equation approach, which produces a conditional distribution for missing data using the proper speciﬁcation for each variable (e.g., OLS regression for continuous variables). ICE then creates multiple data sets using Gibbs sampling techniques (Royston, 2005; van Buuren, 2012). Prior research ﬁndings reveal that the number of data sets be at least equal to the percentage of cases with missing data (Carll, 2017; White, Royston, and Wood, 2009). We create ten unique data sets, which we then combine using the MI command in Stata 15.0 to complete descriptive analyses and multivariate analyses.
