RESULTS
Table 1 presents descriptive statistics for total, militarized, and nonmilitarized property reported by total sample, for currently participating (e.g., values in the year departments participated) and for those police departments that participated in 1033 Program at least once during the study period. Between 1995 and 2016, the U.S. Department of Defense provided slightly more than 48,000 dollars of total supplies per agency nationwide. Although the total cumulative value of militarized property ($26,754) exceeded that of nonmilitarized property ($18,432), the per-capita value of nonmilitarized gear ($1,994 per 10,000 persons) was worth almost twice that of militarized gear ($1,002 per 10,000 persons). Among agencies that participated at least once in the 1033 Program between 1995 and 2016, the average cumulative value of total property transferred is slightly more than $128,000, including $75,791 of militarized property and $52,280 of nonmilitarized property. Although year-to-year participation is rare, the average annual amount of militarized property transferred is quite large. Each year, participating departments receive almost $80,000 per 10,000 persons in total property from the 1033 Program, including $26,513 of militarized property and $52,729 of nonmilitarized property.
