participated in the 1033 Program at least once during the study period and those that never participated in the 1033 Program between 1995 and 2016. Looking ﬁrst at the minority threat variables, agencies that have participated in the 1033 Program represent places with signiﬁcantly higher Black populations (9.7 percent versus 8.6 percent) and Hispanic populations (8.9 percent versus 7.2 percent) than agencies that have not participated. Although these numbers are slightly smaller than the national average for this period, the small mean values reﬂect the large number of small places in the data set and increasing residential “macro-segregation” in which Black–White and Hispanic–White segregation within places (e.g., big cities) has declined, but segregation between places has increased signiﬁcantly over the past two decades as afﬂuent Whites cluster in ex-urban communities, offsetting the increasing diversity of the central cities (Lichter, Parisi, and Taquino, 2015). Recent studies of metro and nonmetro Census places have yielded similar placelevel percentages of Black and Hispanic populations (Lichter, Parisi, and Taquino, 2015; Parisi, Lichter, and Taquino, 2015).
We turn next to rational choice explanations of 1033 Program participation. On average, local police departments in the United States are cities and towns with an average of 165 violent crimes per 10,000 population and counties with 47.5 drug arrests (sales and possession) per 10,000 county population. These numbers are similar to prior research in which the UCR over the same time period was used (Beck and Goldstein, 2017; Feldmeyer, Harris, and Lai, 2016). When we compare the violent crime rates for participating and nonparticipating departments, violent crime rates are signiﬁcantly higher in agencies that have participated in the 1033 Program (189 per 10,000 population) than for agencies that have not participated in the 1033 Program (150 per 10,000 population). Similarly, the county drug arrest rates for agencies that have participated in the 1033 Program (49 per 10,000 population) are slightly higher than the county drug arrest for agencies that have not participated in the 1033 Program (45 per 10,000 population). As police fatalities and terror attacks are extremely rare events, there are minimal differences in ofﬁcer deaths or terror attacks across departments that participated in the 1033 Program and those that did not.
There are signiﬁcant differences in our control variables as well. Compared with never participated departments, those that participated at least once have signiﬁcantly higher poverty and unemployment rates, and have served larger populations and geographies. Notably, there is little difference between participating and nonparticipating agencies in terms of ofﬁcers per capita, distance to DLA disposition centers, or proportion of Republican voters in participating places which is similar to the total sample.
