We turn next to our tests of nonlinearity between minority threat and 1033 Program participation. After controlling for local and regional factors and practical concerns associated with policing and 1033 Program participation, we found a curvilinear relationship between the size of the Black population and successfully acquiring any property from the 1033 Program. Speciﬁcally, the signiﬁcant and positive coefﬁcient for the linear term and the signiﬁcant and negative coefﬁcient for the quadratic term indicate that the true relationship is curvilinear, increasing at a decreasing rate. Speciﬁcally, as the Black population in a city or town increases, police departments are more likely to participate in the 1033 Program, but the strength of this relationship decreases as the size of the Black population increases. Although there is a curvilinear relationship between the size of the Black population and 1033 Program participation, the relative size of the Hispanic population has no effect on whether a department successfully acquired 1033 Program property. Notably, when we tested the nonlinear relationship between percent Black or percent Hispanic and 1033 Program participation, we found no evidence that this relationship took an exponential form (see appendices E and G in the online supporting information).
For agencies that successfully acquire militarized property through the 1033 Program, we found a nonlinear relationship between the relative size of Black populations in their jurisdictions and the value of equipment they receive each year. The functional form of this relationship for Black minority threat, however, is exponential and increases at an increasing rate. Moreover, although we did not ﬁnd a nonlinear relationship for Hispanic populations and the acquisition of materiel through the 1033 Program, the relative size of the Hispanic population is signiﬁcantly associated with the total property value transferred through the 1033 Program. Similar to the Black population, the functional form of this relationship is exponential and increases at an increasing rate. We tested whether the nonlinear relationship between percent Black or percent Hispanic and the value of militarized property received took a quadratic form, but we found no evidence of quadratic functions of minority threat for either Black or Hispanic populations (see appendices F and G in the online supporting information).
In our models for nonmilitarized property in table 3, evidence exists that departments in places with higher local violent crime rates are more likely to acquire nonmilitarized property from the 1033 Program than agencies with lower crime rates, but that crime has no effect on the value of the property received by participating agencies. We ﬁnd no evidence that county drug arrest rates, police fatalities, or recent terror attacks inﬂuence the likelihood of acquiring nonmilitarized equipment via the 1033 Program. Importantly, we

