To summarize, rational choice perspectives of public safety explain 1033 Program participation for the purposes of acquiring both militarized and nonmilitarized property, but they cannot explain differences in the value of total 1033 Program property transferred. Speciﬁcally, departments who reported higher violent crime rates or lower drug arrest rates are more likely to acquire militarized and nonmilitarized property from the 1033 Program. Importantly, after considering rational choice explanations, and controlling for several important factors, minority threat variables have a signiﬁcant and pronounced inﬂuence on 1033 Program participation. Moreover, the functional form of minority threat is different in probit models predicting the successful acquisition of property through the 1033 Program and OLS models predicting the value of property transferred to agencies acquiring materiel. Departments in places with larger Black populations are more likely to acquire militarized property through the 1033 Program, but this relationship is curvilinear, increasing at a decreasing rate. For those departments that successfully acquire militarized property, however, there is a nonlinear, exponential relationship between the respective Black and Hispanic populations and the value of property transferred through the 1033 Program that increases at an increasing rate. Finally, the relationship between minority threat variables and 1033 Program participation is signiﬁcant for militarized materiel but not for nonmilitarized property.

DISCUSSION AND CONCLUSION
In this study, we use a large and unique data set on the value of military equipment obtained by police departments through the Department of Defense’s 1033 Program between 1996 and 2016, and we hurdle models to examine the determinants of materiel acquisition by police in the United States. Our results provide support for conventional rational choice arguments claiming that participation in the 1033 Program is a response to higher violent crime rates. Consistent support exists, however, for minority threat arguments that 1033 Program participation is associated with the presence of Black and Hispanic residents in law enforcement jurisdictions for both odds of involvement and the value of materiel acquired. The form of this minority threat varies across the different steps on 1033 Program participation in ways that have signiﬁcant implications for the policing of minority populations in the United States, yet are consistent with the ﬁndings of previous work on criminal justice resource allocation and minority threat (Blalock, 1967; Jackson, 1989; Jackson and Carroll, 1981; Kent and Jacobs, 2005; Stults and Baumer, 2007; Stucky, 2005; Wang and Mears, 2010).
Regarding rational public choice explanations of LEA participation in the 1033 Program, departments with higher violent crime rates were more likely to participate in the Program and received more valuable equipment, both military and nonmilitary, when they did participate. These ﬁndings reﬂect arguments made by proponents of militarization and heads of departments participating in the 1033 Program (Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Cowper, 2000; Harris et al., 2017). Departments facing high demands to curb violent crime are likely to respond with any technological or procedural changes they believe will help them (Campbell and Campbell, 2009). Interestingly, departments in counties with higher drug arrest rates were less likely to participate in the 1033 Program and received

28

RAMEY & STEIDLEY

less valuable materiel when doing so. This may be a result of drug interdiction efforts in counties that produce lower levels of drug arrests seeking out equipment through the 1033 Program to enhance their ability to make arrests, whereas departments in counties with higher arrest rates already have established drug law enforcement capacities that do not perceive a need to seek military equipment (Harris et al., 2017).
As for our other research questions, we ﬁnd that the relative size of minority populations is consistently and nonlinearly associated with 1033 Program participation. Specifically, the presence of minority populations is associated only with LEA acquisitions of militarized equipment (e.g., weapons, vehicles, and fatigues) from the 1033 Program but not of nonmilitarized equipment (e.g., tools and medical supplies). This ﬁnding, speciﬁc to combat equipment, provides support for the argument that police militarization is, in part, a product of racial threat mechanisms. Speciﬁcally, as the relative size of the Black population in places increases, police departments are more likely to acquire surplus military equipment, and as both Black and Hispanic populations increase, the supplies LEAs successfully acquire are worth more money. These ﬁndings supplement past studies in which minority populations and formal social control efforts were linked (Jackson, 1989; Kane, 2003; Kent and Jacobs, 2005; Stucky, 2005).
Moreover, our ﬁndings add to this literature because we looked for different nonlinear forms of minority threat (Blalock, 1967; Stults and Baumer, 2007; Wang and Mears, 2010).14 By testing for the effect of quadratic forms of minority presence, we found that LEA selection into 1033 Program participation is consistent with a curvilinear minority threat curve, increasing at a decreasing rate, and is only signiﬁcant for Black populations. This ﬁnding may indicate that, controlling for rational public choice demands, LEAs seek surplus military equipment as a response to threats from exclusively Black communities until Blacks make up approximately 27.5 percent of a community. As such, 1033 Program participation seems to be less likely when minority threats are low from Black populations, or once Blacks make up a sizable component of the community. No such ﬁnding was found for Hispanic populations, which may indicate that Black populations present greater perceived threats that motivate LEAs to seek materiel.
We similarly found nonlinear effects for minority group presence in the amount of materiel that LEAs successfully acquire. For both Black and Hispanic populations, the amount of 1033 Program combat materiel increased exponentially as anticipated with Blalock’s (1967) expectations of a minority power threat curve. Such a ﬁnding indicates that although the decision of LEAs to participate in the 1033 Program increases at a decreasing rate with Black populations only, the amount of materiel received increases at an increasing rate for both Black and Hispanic populations. We recognize that the effects sizes displayed in ﬁgures 3 and 4 suggest that differences in minority composition do not account for large differences in the expected per-capita value of militarized property across LEAs (e.g., the expected difference in property value for a 1 percent difference is between $14 and $68 in materiel per 10,000 persons). The values displayed in our ﬁgures reﬂect expected differences for all LEAs, however, and not just those participating in the 1033 Program. As such, small differences in the Black populations (e.g., 2.5 percent) are associated with a 1 standard deviation difference in expected militarized property

