value ($169.86 per 10,000; see table 1). Furthermore, it is important to note, for many small agencies, even small differences in the value of militarized items is likely to have a sizable impact on police inventories and local perceptions of law enforcement (Balko, 2013; Brunswick, 2015; Feldman, 2014; Fowler, 2017; Harris et al., 2017). Overall, our ﬁndings indicated that LEAs seem to request 1033 Program resources in a pattern that emulates what scholars often ﬁnd in work on police expenditures (Jackson, 1989; Jackson and Carroll, 1981; Kent and Jacobs, 2005).
Overall, these ﬁndings suggest that minority group threat can, in part, account for police acquisition of military equipment. Assuming that 1033 Program participation constitutes an effort of police militarization, this study complements extant work on racial discrimination and the criminal justice system. Racial disparities in policing have roots in systems of racial social control, including slavery and Jim Crow (Alexander, 2012). Additionally, the fact that Black populations, but not Hispanic populations, seem to matter when it comes to initially acquiring militarized property also reﬂects the fact that White majorities have long viewed large Black populations as a signiﬁcant economic threat because overt historical institutions of slavery and legal discrimination have been subverted (Alexander, 2012; Du Bois, 1994 [1903]; Hinton, 2016). Once departments successfully acquire property, however, the value of militarized property received is consistent with social control responses in which overwhelming force is used toward both Black and Hispanic minority populations, reﬂecting a threat-oriented approach rooted in symbolic forms of discrimination (Blalock, 1967). This ﬁnding is further bolstered by the fact that minority threat explanations only account for military equipment acquisitions and not for noncombat gear from the 1033 Program.
The ﬁndings from this research can potentially inform policy decisions about acquisition and use of military equipment by local and state law enforcement. We agree with Balko (2013) that police agencies should make information publicly available on not only the 1033 Program equipment they have acquired but also on how often it is used and in what capacity. Making public data to assess the use (or misuse) of military equipment is wise for a few reasons. First, such disclosures allow the public a means to hold the police accountable for their use of military equipment. Additionally, given the fact that we ﬁnd that minority presence is signiﬁcantly associated with 1033 Program participation, a policy of disclosure may help address or illuminate racial biases and tensions that may emerge from police militarization (Meeks, 2006). Finally, it is important to determine whether the acquisition of these materials changes the policing practices of a department (whether for good or for ill; Cowper, 2000; Harris et al., 2017; cf. Buerger, 2000; Kraska, 1996). Accurate data on the acquisition and use of military equipment allows for empirical program evaluations that may inform police departments on the actual effectiveness or ineffectiveness of military equipment used in police work. We also think it is important to acknowledge the role that terrorism and risk to police do not play in 1033 Program participation. These research ﬁndings show that terrorist attacks and ofﬁcer fatalities cannot account for participation in the 1033 Program. Although police militarization as a response to the “war on terror” is expected from a rational public choice perspective, we ﬁnd no support for such a trend in the 1033 Program data.
Even though our results provide support for minority threat accounts of 1033 Program participation and police militarization, several limitations of the current study merit further consideration. First, although we argue that 1033 Program participation is part of the

30

RAMEY & STEIDLEY

broader phenomenon of police militarization, we assess only one dimension of that phenomenon. Police militarization goes well beyond participation in the 1033 Program and the acquisition of materiel; it permeates the organizational and cultural environments of police work (Kraska, 2007). Nevertheless, this material dimension of militarization has captured public attention in ways that other aspects of militarization have not. Although the creation of PPUs and their deployments have increased steadily over the past 50 years, recent pictures of police ofﬁcers riding on MRAPs and other armored vehicles are what make the local and national news outlets (Hutchins, 2014; Welna, 2014). Additionally, the acquisition of military equipment may enable the other dimensions of militarization. For example, surplus vehicles, uniforms, and weapons may foster a combat mentality among ofﬁcers that encourages overpolicing in a militarized context (Kraska, 1996). The 1033 Program may play a role in this process, but we cannot speak to whether 1033 Program participation affects cultural and organizational dynamics in police work.
Another limitation is that our data cannot speak to LEAs that seek out materiel from private vendors using their own funds or grant monies from federal agencies like the Department of Homeland Security. To illustrate this limitation, consider two hypothetical LEAs that each seek to purchase an armored vehicle. If one agency were to purchase the vehicle from a private vendor rather than using 1033 Program to acquire it, then our data would not capture that transaction. We must be cautious not to equate 1033 Program participation as a uniform indicator of police militarization, as we cannot account for these other private sources of materiel. Similarly, the DLA only includes values for property that has been transferred to law enforcement; thus, our dependent variable only captures successfully acquired property and not all equipment requested in a given year.
We maintain, however, that our assessment of police militarization using 1033 Program participation is appropriate for several reasons. The 1033 Program is unique as the value of surplus materiel from the DoD is provided at only shipping cost and with less oversight than comparable approaches that might use grant funds or tax money. We would argue that these incentives for LEAs to use the 1033 Program over private vendors are strong. Furthermore, recent research ﬁndings and statements by the DLA indicate that the role of the federal government is limited to the timing of available equipment as a result of year-to-year changes in military engagement globally, geographical location of the storage and the distance of shipping centers to LEAs, agencies’ past acquisitions and cumulative value of property accumulated over time, the land area covered by law enforcement, and the ability of LEA administration to complete the application and transfer process successfully (Bruce et al., 2017; Grasso, 2014; Harris et al., 2017). With the exception of the application process itself, we believe that we have controlled for many of these factors in our models.15 Ultimately, we are interested in examining where materiel is going and whether rational public choice or minority threat accounts of police militarization help to explain the distribution of military equipment. We feel this approach speaks to the

