concern of citizens patrolled by police forces using military gear, as well as expands current knowledge about the ecological determinants of police militarization (Ajilore, 2015; Balko, 2013; Bove and Gavrilova, 2017; Bruce et al., 2017; Harris et al., 2017; Insler et al., 2017).
Finally, although traditional measures of racial threat include the relative size of the non-White population, other racial and ethnic dynamics are not considered in this article that likely have important implications for police militarization. For example, Ajilore (2015) found that racial segregation, and not racial composition, was associated with increased odds of acquiring MRAPs. Similarly, race or ethnic-speciﬁc measures of economic or political threat may better capture competition for jobs or political power that motivate respective economic or political threat responses. A more comprehensive and causally powerful test of minority threat arguments in police militarization necessitates a theoretical assessment of both racial and ethnic perceptions of threat from the White majority (i.e., is minority threat viewed as political or economic in nature, and does militarization reduce the threat?) and racially speciﬁc measures to account for those threats independent of minority presence (e.g., Black and Hispanic employment or voting age population; Shah, 2018; Stults and Baumer, 2007, Wang and Mears, 2010). Our purpose here, however, is to illustrate the importance of race in police militarization arguments and to guide future research in this effort. The presence of signiﬁcant positive and nonlinear relationships between the Black and Hispanic composition and 1033 Program participation provides early evidence that minority threat and racialized social control may inﬂuence police militarization independently of rational public choice accounts.
Future research should be aimed at considering two important questions. First, what are the implications of police militarization in general and participation in the 1033 Program in particular? Alongside the growing attention given to police militarization in the public and the press, there has been increased scrutiny involving police interaction with citizens, particularly young Black males. Whether confrontations and police violence are increasing along with the rise in police militarization remains an unanswered question. Second, although the 1033 Program provides “free” surplus equipment to local law enforcement, the supplies and equipment still come at public cost. In addition to the federally incurred costs of the initial development and purchase of the military equipment, local governments still take on transportation, maintenance, and storage costs, as well additional personnel costs associated with the deployment of this equipment. Scholars should examine how and whether other public services—including welfare programs, infrastructure, and education—are affected by increased social-control spending on military equipment. Furthermore, scholars need to examine whether increases in militarization and declines in other public services may have an interactive effect.

